description: From Middle English pate, of uncertain origin. Perhaps a shortened form of Old French patene or Medieval Latin patena, both from Latin patina (“pan, dish”). Alternatively, perhaps akin to Old Frisian pote (“skull”).

entries.meaning: (somewhat archaic) The head, particularly the top or crown.
examples: He had a shiny, bald pate.

description: Attested since circa 1700, from French pâté, from Old French paste, pastée. Doublet of pâté.

entries.meaning: Alternative spelling of pâté (finely-ground paste of meat, fish, etc.)
The interior body, or non-rind portion of cheese, described by its texture, density, and color.
